#, no-wrap
msgid "star ratings & color labels"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Star ratings and color labels help you to sort and rank images according to your own criteria. An image's star rating and color labels can be displayed over thumbnails in the lighttable view and filmstrip module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "star ratings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can give an image a rating from zero to five stars. Whenever you import images, each image receives a default rating which you can define in the [import](../../../getting-started/import.md) module.  You can also mark an image as “rejected”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are several ways to change a rating. While hovering the cursor over an image thumbnail, you can press a number key 0 – 5 to define the number of stars, or press R to “reject” an image. This is probably the fastest way to rate your images on first inspection of a film roll.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can also directly click on the star icons that are overlaid on the thumbnails or in the bottom panel. Click the x to reject.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As rejecting an image removes the currently-applied star rating, you can undo the rejection by clicking x or pressing R again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "Export images that have been selected in the lighttable or the filmstrip of the darkroom view. \n"
msgid "To rate multiple images at once, select those images in the lighttable or filmstrip and then press the appropriate shortcut key.\n"
msgstr "Eksportu bildojn elektitajn en la lumtablo aŭ la filmbendo de la senluma ĉambra vido. \n"

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color labels"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Color labels are another way to classify images, and can be used as an alternative to star ratings or to work alongside them. Each image can carry any combination of one or more color labels (red, yellow, green, blue, or purple).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can set the color labels for a single image by hovering your cursor over the thumbnail and pressing the function keys F1 – F5, which correspond with the labels in the order given above.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/star-color.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "To set the color labels of one or more images, select the desired images in the lighttable or filmstrip and then press the appropriate shortcut key or click the corresponding color button in the bottom panel. A color label will be added to all selected images if **any** of them do not currently have the label; otherwise the label will be removed from all selected images. To remove all labels (of any color) from the selected images, press the gray button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "image grouping"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Grouping images helps to improve the structure and clarity of your image collection when displayed in the lighttable view.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can combine images into a group by selecting them and using the global menu _Image_ 🡒 _Group images_, or by pressing Ctrl+G. Likewise, you can remove selected images from a group by clicking the “ungroup” button, or pressing Ctrl+Shift+G.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Duplicated images are automatically grouped together. Similarly, if you import multiple images from the same directory, having the same base name, but different extensions (eg. `IMG_1234.CR2` and `IMG_1234.JPG`), those images automatically form a group.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Images that are members of a group are denoted by a group icon ![top panel_grouping icon](top-panel_grouping.jpg).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This icon also appears as a button, in the top panel of the lighttable view, that can be used to toggle grouping on and off. If grouping is off, all images are displayed as individual thumbnails. If grouping is on, the images in a group are represented by a single thumbnail image (the group leader). If you press the group icon in the group leader's thumbnail, that group is expanded (click a second time to collapse). If you then expand another group, the first group collapses.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "An expanded group in the filemanager mode of lighttable view is indicated by an orange frame that appears as soon as your mouse pointer hovers over one of the images. This frame surrounds all images in the group.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can define which image is considered to be the group leader by clicking on the group icon of the desired image while that group is expanded. The group icon is shown only if grouping mode is enabled, so to change the group leader, you need to first enable grouping, expand the appropriate group and finally click the group icon of the desired \"group leader\" image. The current group leader is shown in a tooltip when you hover over the group icon of an image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you collapse an image group and then enter darkroom mode (e.g. by double-clicking on the thumbnail), the group leader image will be opened for developing.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Image groups are also a convenient way to protect an existing history stack against unintentional changes. If you have just finalized an image and want to protect its current version, simply select the image, click “duplicate” in the selected images panel, and make sure that grouping is switched on and that the group is collapsed. Now, whenever you open the image group again in the darkroom, only the group leader will be altered. The underlying duplicate will remain unchanged.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/digital-asset-management/grouping.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** “duplicating images” only generates a copy of an image's history stack, stored in another small XMP file. There is still only one raw file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/lighttable/_index.md content/getting-started/keyboard.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Lighttable"
msgstr "lumtablo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The lighttable view is the default view loaded when Ansel is started, and allows you to view and manage your image collection. It will noticeably allow you to:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"- cull your images, assign then ratings and ultimately decide which images are worth keeping and editing,\n"
"- filter your images based on ratings, base folder, or any metadata supported by the software (EXIF/IPTC/XMP),\n"
"- apply metadata, like title, description, tags, GPS coordinates, or correct EXIF date/time,\n"
"- copy-paste editing histories between images or apply styles, individually or in batches,\n"
"- export images editing histories to final files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/lighttable/_index.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "Lighttable"
msgid "Lighttable content"
msgstr "lumtablo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "All the images known to Ansel are stored in a database, the [library](../../install/configuration.md). The lighttable shows thumbnails of a subset of this library, called a _collection_. A collection is created by filtering the images from the library using criteria, first from the [library toolbox](../toolboxes/collections.md), then from filtering/include toolbar.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Library\n"
": The library toolbox, in the left sidebar, provides the primary querying criteria to extract a subset of images from the library database. The main criteria are :\n"
"    - __Folders__ : the base folder in which the images are stored on your filesystem. They can be shown as a flat list or as a tree. Note that Ansel does not directly read the folder's content, but shows its [imported](../../getting-started/import.md) images (from its database) whose base folder matches this criterion. As such, the actual filesystem folder may contain more images than what Ansel will show, if they have not been imported.\n"
"    - __Collections__ : allows to query all images that have a certain tag assigned. This is similar to what other software call \"collections\" or \"virtual folders\", except that, in Ansel, you don't add an image to a virtual folder, you assign a tag to an image, and then query all images having that tag.\n"
"    - __Queries__ : enables more advanced querying rules, using metadata and boolean combinations of criteria (or/and/and not). Note that _folders_ and _collections_ (aka _tags_) only provide a simplified interface for the most common fields that can be found in the _queries_ tab. Available metadata to filter can be:\n"
"        - __gear__ : lens name, camera, focal length,\n"
"        - __exposure settings__ : shutterspeed, ISO, aperture,\n"
"        - __date and time__ : of the shot, of last modification, last export, last print, etc.\n"
"        - __user set data__ : title, description, copyright, creator, publisher, etc.\n"
"        - __internal technical tags__ : file format, local copies, etc.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/lighttable/_index.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Include\n"
": The _include_ toolbar, in the second top row, allows to quickly filter in and out images based on their (_in order of appearance_):\n"
"    - __rating__ :\n"
"        - unrated (0 star) : the barred star icon,\n"
"        - _rejected_ state : the circled cross icon (same as on the thumbnails),\n"
"        - 1 to 5 stars : the next 5 star icons. Those are positional, meaning :\n"
"            - selecting the third starred-button will filter in all images having 3 stars,\n"
"            - to select images rated at least 3 stars, you will need to select the third, fourth and fifth stars, which can be quickly achieved with <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>left click</kbd> on the third star.\n"
"    - __color labels__ :\n"
"        - unlabled images : the white disk,\n"
"        - color-labeled images : colored disks,\n"
"    - __edited state__ :\n"
"        - images having no editing history : the horizontally-barred circle,\n"
"        - images having an editing history : the yin-yang +/- circle (same as on the thumbnails),\n"
"    - __selection__ : restricting the collection to any arbitrary user-defined selection. This replaces Darktable's _culling_ view.\n"
"    - __text search__ : restricting the collection to all images having at least one textual property matching the search query (filename, folder, title, etc.).\n"
": The controls from the _include_ toolbar are toggle buttons, meaning when they are selected, images matching those criteria will be shown (filtered in/included), and when they are unselected, images matching those criteria will be hidden (filtered out/excluded). To show everything (_include everything_ or _exclude nothing_), you will therefore need to have all buttons checked, which can be quickly achieved by doing a right click on any of the buttons, then selecting _Select all filters_ in the context menu. If no button is toggled, no image is included and the lighttable grid stays empty.\n"
