#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color balance rgb"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "An advanced module which brings color-grading tools from cinematography into the photographic scene-referred pipeline.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module is not suitable for beginners with no prior knowledge of color theory, who might want to stick to the _global chroma_ and _global vibrance_ settings until they have a good understanding of the [dimensions of color](../../../color-management/color-dimensions.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "find location"
msgid "introduction"
msgstr "trovi lokon"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Color-grading is an important part of image editing. It can help to remove unwanted color casts and can also deliver a creative color twist that will add atmosphere to your images. In the days of film photography, most of the color ambiance was obtained with the film emulsion and the developing chemicals, with some color timing being performed under the enlarger with color heads. This consumed expensive resources and was mostly reserved for the cinema industry, where the job was performed by a colorist.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the digital age, where raw images look flat and even, color-grading assumes the same role that film emulsions did, by re-introducing color shifts for aesthetic purposes. It can also serve to harmonize the color palette of a series of images (which may have been shot under different conditions) to achieve a consistent global look. For this task, the [vectorscope](../../toolboxes/scopes.md#vectorscope) is also extremely useful.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Colorists usually split color-grading into two distinct steps:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1. _Primary color-grading_ aims to fix unwanted color casts and create a neutral starting point,\n"
"2. _Secondary color-grading_ gives the image its final look and atmosphere.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Primary color-grading is best left to the [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) module, which operates in a physical framework better suited to illuminant correction. _Color balance RGB_, on the other hand, is mostly concerned with secondary color-grading. Performing a truly neutral primary color-grading should make the secondary color-grading easy to transfer between images (via styles, presets or copy & paste) with a similar effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "general settings"
msgid "general principles"
msgstr "ĝeneralaj agordoj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The _color balance RGB_ module is an improvement over the [American Society of Cinematographers Color Decision List](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASC_CDL) (ASC CDL), and uses alpha masks to allow the effect to be properly split between shadows and highlights. The classic CDL acts on the entire luminance range, and each of its parameters is given more weight on some parts of the image only as a side-effect of the mathematics.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module works, for the most part (_4 ways_, _chroma_, _vibrance_, _contrast_), in a linear RGB color space designed specifically for color-grading. This color space exhibits a uniform spacing of perceptual hues while retaining a physically-scaled luminance[^1]. The perceptual part of the module (_saturation_ and _brilliance_) works in the JzAzBz[^2] color space, which provides a perceptual scaling of both lightness and chromaticity suitable for HDR images. Both color spaces ensure that saturation and chroma changes take place at constant hue, which is not the case for most other saturation operators in Ansel (notably in the older [_color balance RGB_](./color-balance-rgb.md) module).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Link reference
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "[^1]: Richard A. Kirk, Chromaticity coordinates for graphic arts based on CIE 2006 LMS with even spacing of Munsell colours, 2019."
msgstr ""

#. type: Link reference
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "[^2]: Safdar et al., Perceptually uniform color space for image signals including high dynamic range and wide gamut, 2017. <https://doi.org/10.1364/OE.25.015131>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The _color balance RGB_ module expects a scene-referred linear input and produces a scene-referred RGB output, which may or may not be linear, depending on the module settings (_contrast_ and _power_ will delinearize the output).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "At its output, _color balance RGB_ checks that the graded colors fit inside the pipeline RGB color space (Rec 2020 by default) and applies a soft saturation clipping at constant hue, aiming to retarget out-of-gamut color to the nearest in-gamut color by scaling both chroma and lightness. This prevents the chroma and saturation settings from pushing colors outside of the valid range and allows more drastic adjustments to be safely used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_Note that this module abides by the CIE definitions of chroma and saturation, as explained in the [dimensions of color](../../../color-management/color-dimensions.md) section._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "images tab"
msgid "master tab"
msgstr "langeto de bildoj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue shift\n"
": Rotate all colors in the image by an angle over the chromaticity plane, at constant luminance and chroma. You can use this control to remove spilled colored light on a subject or to quickly change the color of some object. This setting is usually best applied locally, using [masks](../../../views/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"global vibrance\n"
": This affects the chroma dimension of color over the entire image, prioritizing those colors with low chroma. This allows the chroma of neutral colors to be increased without exaggerating already-colorful pixels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"contrast\n"
": This setting is applied on the luminance channel at constant hue and chroma. The fulcrum setting (in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab, under _contrast gray fulcrum_) allows you to set the neutral point of the contrast curve:\n"
": - at the fulcrum, the contrast curve leaves the luminance unchanged,\n"
": - below the fulcrum, the contrast curve decreases the luminance for positive contrast values, or increases it for negative values,\n"
": - above the fulcrum, the contrast curve increases the luminance for positive contrast values, or decreases it for negative values.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": The fulcrum has a value of 18.45% by default, which is consistent with the current scene-referred workflow and should fit most use cases (assuming that global brightness has been fixed as recommended using the [_exposure_](./exposure.md) module).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": The contrast algorithm gives natural results that mimic the central part of the contrast curve of analog film. However, it will also increase the image's dynamic range, which may void _filmic_ settings in the pipe. For global contrast adjustments, you should normally use the [_tone equalizer_](./tone-equalizer.md) module -- the _color balance RGB_ contrast slider is best used with masks, e.g. for selective corrections over the foreground or background.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "linear chroma grading"
msgstr "lineara kolorogradigo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Linear chroma grading affects the chroma dimension proportionally to its input value, at constant hue and luminance. It does this globally, with a flat coefficient (using the _global chroma_), as well as on each of the _shadows_, _mid-tones_ and _highlights_ masks (defined in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab under _luminance ranges_).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "perceptual saturation grading"
msgstr "percepta saturiĝa gradigo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Perceptual saturation grading affects both the luminance and the chroma dimensions, in a perceptual space, proportionally to its input value, at constant hue. It does this globally, with a flat coefficient (using the _global saturation_), as well as on each of the _shadows_, _mid-tones_ and _highlights_ masks (defined in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab under _luminance ranges_).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "perceptual brilliance grading"
msgstr "percepta brileca gradigo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Perceptual brilliance grading affects both the luminance and the chroma dimensions, in a perceptual space, proportionally to its input value, at constant hue, and in a direction orthogonal to the saturation. Its effect is close to that of changing exposure, but scaled perceptually. It does this globally, with a flat coefficient (using the _global saturation_), as well as on each of the _shadows_, _mid-tones_ and _highlights_ masks (defined in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab under _luminance ranges_).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "images tab"
msgid "4 ways tab"
msgstr "langeto de bildoj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each of the settings in the 4 ways tab is composed of the same three components, which define a color using independent coordinates:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"1. _luminance_,\n"
"2. _hue_,\n"
"3. _chroma_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Color input like this defines a color shift applied to the image globally or over the specified luminance range.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Each hue slider has a color picker, which may be used to compute the opponent color of the selected region. This is useful to revert unwanted color casts (e.g. skin redness), since shifting the color to its opponent cast neutralizes it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "global options"
msgid "global offset"
msgstr "tutmondaj opcioj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is equivalent to the ASC CDL _offset_ and falls back to adding a constant RGB value to all pixels, quite like the _black offset_ in the _exposure_ module. This control does not use masking.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "shadows lift"
msgstr "ombra levigo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is conceptually equivalent to the _lift_ from _lift/gamma/gain_, although implemented differently, and falls back to multiplying the masked pixels by a constant RGB value. It is applied using the _shadows_ mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "highlights gain"
msgstr "brilaĵa gajno"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is equivalent to the ASC CDL _slope_, and falls back to multiplying a the masked pixels by a constant RGB value. It is applied using the _highlights_ mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "global options"
msgid "global power"
msgstr "tutmondaj opcioj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is equivalent to the ASC CDL _power_, and falls back to applying a constant RGB exponent. It is not masked and needs to be normalized, since the power function has a different behaviour above and below 1, and we are in an unbounded pipeline where white is typically greater than 1. The normalization parameter is available in the [_masks_](#masks-tab) tab under _white fulcrum_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "images tab"
msgid "masks tab"
msgstr "langeto de bildoj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-balance-rgb.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This tab defines auxiliary controls for the previous tabs. Masking controls typically don't require any user modification since the defaults are calibrated to suit most needs and fulfil the normal scene-referred pixel pipeline expectations. You should only need to change these settings in specific scenarios.\n"
