#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "rgb curve"
msgstr "rvb kurbo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A classic digital photography tool to alter an image's tones using curves.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Activate the color picker on the left to show the picked values in the graph (Ctrl+click or right-click to use the picker in area mode). Numerical (Lab) values of the input and output (see below) at the selected spot or area are shown at the top left of the widget.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A second color picker to the right can be used to automtaically create new nodes based on the sampled area. Ctrl+click+drag to alter the created nodes to have a positive curve for the selected area; Shift+click+drag to create a negative curve.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": RGB is a linear color space designed to capture and display images in additive synthesis. It is related to the capture and display media and does not isolate color and lightness information in the same way that Lab and XYZ color spaces do. This module works in ProPhoto RGB. Adding contrast in RGB space is known to desaturate highlights and boost saturation in the shadows, but this has been proven to be the most reliable way to edit contrast, and is the standard method in most software\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": Depending on the desired intent you can apply the RGB curve in two different modes\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _RGB, linked channels_: Apply the L-channel curve to all three channels in the RGB color space.\n"
": - _RGB, independent channels_: R, G and B curves can be adjusted independently.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"compensate middle gray\n"
": Select this to change the histogram display in the module. This option does not alter the processing but may assist when editing the curve.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color zones"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Selectively adjust the lightness, saturation and hue of pixels based on their current lightness, saturation and hue.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module works in CIE LCh color space, which separates pixels into _lightness_, chroma (_saturation_) and _hue_ components. It allows you to manipulate the lightness, saturation and hue of targeted groups of pixels through the use of curves.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You first need to choose whether you wish to adjust (select) pixels based on their lightness, saturation or hue. You can then use three curves, on their respective tabs, to adjust the lightness, saturation and hue of ranges of pixels selected via this method.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_**Note:** This module should be used with care, as transitions between colors may not be graceful. Instead, use the [color balance rgb](./color-balance-rgb.md) module with a [parametric mask](../masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md)._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "pixel selection method"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The _color zones_ module offers three different methods for selecting which pixels you want to adjust. They are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select by hue (default)\n"
": Select pixels to manipulate based on their hue. For example, you may want to darken a blue sky, or to change a red porche into a yellow one. The following image shows the full range of hues that you can choose to operate on:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "![color-assessment-overview](./color-assessment/color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"
msgid ": ![color zones choose hue](color-zones-choose-hue.jpg)\n"
msgstr "![color-assessment-overview](color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select by lightness\n"
": Select pixels to manipulate based on their lightness. For example, you may want to make your shadows brighter, or to make your highlights more yellow. The following image shows the range of lightness levels that you can choose to operate on, from dark to light:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "![color-assessment-overview](./color-assessment/color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"
msgid ": ![color zones choose lightness](color-zones-choose-lightness.jpg)\n"
msgstr "![color-assessment-overview](color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select by saturation\n"
": Select pixels to manipulate based on their saturation. For example, you may want to tone down the saturation of some already highly saturated pixels, or to change their hue. The following image shows the range of saturation levels that you can choose to operate on, from a completely unsaturated monochrome gray through to the most highly saturated color:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "![color-assessment-overview](./color-assessment/color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"
msgid ": ![color zones choose saturation](color-zones-choose-saturation.jpg)\n"
msgstr "![color-assessment-overview](color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "pixel manipulation curves"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have chosen a pixel selection method, the selected range of lightness, saturation or hue levels will appear along the horizontal axis of the three pixel manipulation curves, which can be viewed and adjusted by choosing the appropriate tab (lightness, saturation, hue).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If, for example, you were to choose to _select by hue_ (the default), the horizontal axis (below the manipulation curves) would show the range of hues you can work with, and the three pixel manipulation curves would appears as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lightness\n"
": By adjusting the lightness curve up or down in a given (hue) location, you can brighten or darken pixels matching hues where the curve has been raised or lowered, respectively. In the example below the blue sky in an image has been darkened for dramatic effect:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "![color-assessment-overview](./color-assessment/color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"
msgid ": ![color zones adjust lightness](color-zones-adjust-lightness.jpg)\n"
msgstr "![color-assessment-overview](color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": By adjusting the saturation curve up or down in a given (hue) location, you can desaturate (make less colorful) or resaturate (make more colorful) pixels matching hues where the curve has been raised or lowered, respectively. In the example below, a red object in the background has been desaturated so it is less of a distraction to the main subject of the photo:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": ![color zones adjust saturation](color-zones-adjust-saturation.jpg)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": By adjusting the hue curve up or down in a given (hue) location, you can shift the hue of pixels matching hues where the curve has been raised or lowered, allowing you to replace one color with another. In the example below, a pink toy in an image has been changed to blue:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "![color-assessment-overview](./color-assessment/color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"
msgid ": ![color zones adjust hue](color-zones-adjust-hue.jpg)\n"
msgstr "![color-assessment-overview](color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The curves work similarly in the lightness- and saturation-based selection modes as well.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Note that these examples are somewhat contrived in order to illustrate the module's usage. In practical use, they would likely need to be combined with [drawn](..//masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) and/or [parametric](../masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md) masks to further isolate their effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "range selection"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "When adjusting the pixel manipulation curves, it can sometimes be difficult to judge exactly where on the horizontal axis pixels will fall. To the right of the tab controls are a pair of color pickers that can be used to assist with this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you click the left-hand color picker and choose a pixel in the image, you will see a dark vertical line showing where that pixel falls on the horizontal axis. If you Ctrl+click or right-click on the same color picker you can choose a rectangular area from the image -- the range of values represented within the selected rectangle will be shaded vertically, with a similar dark line showing the median value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you click on the right-hand color picker, you can similarly choose a rectangular area on the image and the display will be shown as described above (a shaded area with a dark vertical line). However, in this case the color picker will also automatically add some control points to the curve for you, representing the highlighted range (see below). Simply drag on the center node to raise or lower the curve within the selected range. Alternatively, hold Ctrl while selecting a range to automatically create a positive curve (push up the selected range) or hold Shift while selecting to create a negative curve (pushed down).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "![color-assessment-overview](./color-assessment/color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"
msgid "![color zones overview](color-zones-overview.jpg)\n"
msgstr "![color-assessment-overview](color-assessment-overview.jpg)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid ": The following modules are excluded from the _copy_ operation:\n"
msgid "The following controls are available in the _color zones_ module:\n"
msgstr ": La jenaj moduloj estas ekskluditaj de la _kopio_ operacio:\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lightness, saturation & hue tabs\n"
": Each tab displays a pixel manipulation curve to allow you to alter “lightness”, “saturation”, or “hue” based on the pixel selection method.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"edit by area\n"
": Choose how to interact with the curve. This setting is disabled by default, allowing the control points for the curve to be freely placed. Check the box to fall back to the legacy \"edit by area\" mode, which functions in a similar way to the spline curve controls used in wavelet modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
" ![mask-icon](icon-mask.jpg) mask display\n"
": Enable the _mask display_ to highlight pixels that have been affected by _color zones_ adjustments in yellow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"select by\n"
": Define the horizontal axis (the range of values to work on). You can choose between “lightness”, “saturation”, and “hue” (the default). Changing this parameter resets all pixel manipulation curves to their default state (horizontal straight lines). If you want to work on multiple ranges, you need to create additional instances of the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"process mode\n"
": Choose between a “smooth” (default) or “strong” processing mode. The default mode is less likely to cause artifacts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mix\n"
": Use this parameter to tune the strength of the overall effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/color-zones.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"interpolation method\n"
": Define how the curve is interpolated using the user-defined control points.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "rotate and perspective"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automatically correct for converging lines, a form of perspective distortion. The underlying mechanism is inspired by Markus Hebel's [_ShiftN_](http://www.shiftn.de/) program. This module also allows for the rotation of the image to be adjusted.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Perspective distortions are a natural effect when projecting a three dimensional scene onto a two dimensional plane and cause objects close to the viewer to appear larger than objects further away. Converging lines are a special case of perspective distortions frequently seen in architectural photographs -- parallel lines, when photographed at an angle, are transformed into converging lines that meet at some vantage point within or outside of the image frame.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module is able to correct converging lines by warping the image in such a way that the lines in question become parallel to the image frame. Corrections can be applied in a vertical and horizontal direction, either separately or in combination. In order to perform automatic correction the module is able to analyze the image for suitable structural features consisting of line segments. You can also set the line structures manually by drawing a \"perspective rectangle\" or drawing multiple horizontal and vertical lines onto the image. Based on these (automatic or manually-drawn) line segments a fitting procedure is initiated, which determines the best values for the module's parameters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "As the most common use case for this module is for rotation, the perspective correction controls are hidden by default. Click the \"perspective\" header to expand the controls.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "While the module is active (and none of the structure buttons are selected) you can right-click and drag anywhere on the image to define a horizontal or vertical line. This will cause the rotation parameter to be automatically adjusted to make the drawn line horizontal/vertical with respect to the image frame.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "perspective correction workflow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "structure"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The first step is to obtain details about the horizontal and/or vertical structures in the image. Three alternative methods are provided to do this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "manually draw structure lines"
msgstr "permane desegni strukturajn liniojn"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the ![draw-structure-lines-icon](icon-draw-structure-lines.jpg) and then click on one of the \"fit\" icons to complete the process. You can re-enter this mode to edit your drawn lines at any time. Edit a line by clicking and dragging on the line or the end nodes, and right-click a line to delete it. Once you are happy with your changes, re-select a \"fit\" icon to complete the process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "manually define a perspective rectangle"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the ![draw-structure-rectangle-icon](icon-draw-structure-rectangle.jpg)icon to enable perspective rectangle drawing mode. This will draw a rectangle on the screen and you can grab and move the corners of the rectangle so that the left and right sides fall on lines you wish to make vertical, and the top and bottom fall on lines you wish to make horizontal. Once you are happy with your rectangle, click one of the \"fit\" icons to complete the process. You can re-enter this mode to edit your drawn rectangle at any time. Once you are happy with your changes, re-select a \"fit\" icon to complete the process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "automatically detect structure"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Click the ![get-structure-icon](icon-get-structure.jpg) icon to analyze the image for structural elements -- Ansel will automatically detect and evaluate line elements. Shift+click to apply a contrast enhancement step before performing further analysis. Ctrl+click to apply an edge enhancement step before performing further analysis. Both variations can be used alone or in combination if the default analysis is not able to detect a sufficient number of lines.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Only lines that form a set of vertical or horizontal converging lines are used for subsequent processing steps. Line segments are displayed as overlays on the image canvas, with the type of line identified by color as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"green\n"
": Vertical converging lines\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"red\n"
": Vertical lines that do not converge\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blue\n"
": Horizontal converging lines\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"yellow\n"
": Horizontal lines that do not converge\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"gray\n"
": Other lines that are not of interest to this module\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Lines marked in red or yellow are regarded as outliers and are not taken into account during the automatic fitting step. This outlier elimination involves a statistical process using random sampling which means that each time you press the \"get structure\" button the color pattern of the lines will look slightly different.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can manually change the status of line segments: Left-Click on a line to select it (turn the color to green or blue) and Right-click to deselect it (turn the color to red or yellow). If you keep the mouse button pressed, you can use a sweeping action to select/deselect multiple lines in a row. The size of the select/deselect brush can be changed with the mouse wheel. Hold down the Shift key and keep the left or right mouse button pressed while dragging to select or deselect all lines in the chosen rectangular area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you are happy with the detected lines, select a \"fit\" icon to complete the process.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "fit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you are happy with the identified horizontal and vertical lines, using one of the methods above, click on one of the \"fit\" icons to automatically set the module's parameters based on the defined structure. The image and the overlaid lines are then displayed with perspective corrections applied.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You may choose to automatically apply just the vertical corrections ![vertical-icon](icon-vertical.jpg). Ctrl+click on any of the icons to apply a rotation without the lens shift. Shift+click on any of the icons to apply the lens shift without any rotation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "rotate"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once you are happy with the applied perspective corrections, you may wish to perform a final rotation correction either by adjusting the rotation parameter or right-clicking and dragging the image to define a horizontal/vertical line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"rotation\n"
": Control the rotation of the image around its center to correct for a skewed horizon. To rotate by more than the default soft limit of ten degrees, right click and enter the desired value up to 180 degrees.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"automatic cropping\n"
": When activated, this feature crops the image to remove any black areas at the edges caused by the distortion correction. You can either crop to the \"largest area\", or to the largest rectangle that maintains the original aspect ratio (\"original format\"). In the latter case you can manually adjust the automatic cropping result by clicking in the clip region and moving it around. The size of the region is modified automatically to exclude any black areas.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lens shift (horizontal)\n"
": Correct converging horizontal lines (i.e. to make the _blue_ lines parallel).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lens shift (vertical)\n"
": Correct converging vertical lines (i.e. to make the _green_ lines parallel). In some cases you can obtain a more natural looking image if you correct vertical distortions to an 80 ~ 90% level rather than to the maximum extent. To do this, reduce the correction slider after having performed the automatic correction.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shear\n"
": Shear the image along one of its diagonals. This is required when correcting vertical and horizontal perspective distortions simultaneously.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"guides\n"
": When activated, a grid is overlaid on the image to help you judge the quality of the correction.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lens model\n"
": This parameter controls the lens focal length, camera crop factor and aspect ratio that used by the correction algorithm. If set to \"generic\" a lens focal length of 28mm on a 35mm full-frame camera is assumed. If set to “specific”, the focal length and crop factor can be set manually using the sliders provided.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"focal length\n"
": If the _lens model_ is set to \"specific\", set the lens focal length. The default value is taken from the image's Exif data, and can be overridden by adjusting the slider manually.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"crop factor\n"
": If the _lens model_ is set to \"specific\", set the camera crop factor. You will normally need to set this value manually.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"aspect adjust\n"
": If the _lens model_ is set to \"specific\", this parameter allows for a free manual adjustment of the image's aspect ratio.  This is useful for \"unsqueezing\" images taken with an anamorphic lens (which changes the ratio of image height to width).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"structure\n"
": Define horizontal and vertical lines in the image using a manual or automatic method (see workflow section for details).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/rotate-perspective.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"fit\n"
": Set the distortion correction sliders automatically based on the identified structure (see workflow section for details).\n"
msgstr ""

