#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "sharpen"
msgstr "akrigi"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sharpen the details in the image using a standard UnSharp Mask (USM).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module works by increasing the contrast around edges and thereby enhancing the _impression_ of sharpness of an image. This module is applied to the L channel in Lab color space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "_**Note:** The USM algorithm used in this module performs blurs in Lab color space, which can produce undesirable effects, and is no longer recommended. Instead use the presets offered by the [contrast equalizer](./contrast-equalizer.md) module for deblurring or the [local contrast](./local-contrast.md) module for general sharpness._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radius\n"
": The unsharp mask applies a gaussian blur to the image as part of its algorithm. This parameter controls the radius of that blur which, in turn, defines the spatial extent of the edge enhancement. Very high values will lead to ugly over-sharpening.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"amount\n"
": The strength of the sharpening.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/sharpen.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"threshold\n"
": Contrast differences below this threshold are excluded from sharpening. Use this to avoid amplification of noise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "watermark"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Render a vector-based overlay onto your image. Watermarks are standard SVG documents and can be designed using [Inkscape](http://www.inkscape.org/).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can also use bitmap (PNG) images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The SVG processor in Ansel can also substitute strings within an SVG document, allowing image-dependent information to be included in the watermark.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "User-designed watermarks should be placed into the directory `$HOME/.config/Ansel/watermarks`. Once in place, use the reload button update the list of available watermarks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The following is a list of variable strings that are supported for substitution within an SVG document.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In addition to this list you can also use the variable strings defined in the [variables](../../..//variables.md) section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$(WATERMARK_TEXT)             A short free text (max. 63 characters)\n"
"$(WATERMARK_COLOR)            The color to use for $WATERMARK_TEXT\n"
"$(WATERMARK_FONT_FAMILY)      The font family to use for $WATERMARK_TEXT\n"
"$(WATERMARK_FONT_STYLE)       The font style (normal, oblique, italic)\n"
"$(WATERMARK_FONT_WEIGHT)      The font weight (boldness)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"marker\n"
": Choose the watermark to apply. Use the reload button to update the list to include any newly-added watermarks. The extension of the file (png/svg) is shown in brackets.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"text\n"
": A free text field in which you can enter up to 63 characters to be printed where referenced by the corresponding watermark. An example is supplied as `simple-text.svg`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"text color\n"
": The color of the text. Click on the colored field to open a color selector dialog which offers you a choice of commonly used colors, or allows you to define a color in RGB color space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"text font\n"
": The font to use (default \"DejaVu Sans Book\"). Click on the field to open a dialog box showing the fonts available on your system. Fonts can be searched by name and a preview is shown next to the font name. You may specify your own sample text.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"opacity\n"
": The opacity of the watermark's rendering.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scale\n"
": The scale of the watermark, with respect to the option selected in the \"scale on\" parameter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"rotate\n"
": The rotation angle of the watermark.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scale on\n"
": The reference for the scale parameter. The default setting “image” scales the watermark relative to the horizontal image size. Alternatively you can scale the watermark relative to the “larger border” or “smaller border”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"alignment\n"
": Use these controls to align the watermark to any edge or the center of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"x offset\n"
": Pixel-independent offset relative to the choice of alignment on the x-axis.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"y offset\n"
": Pixel-independent offset relative to the choice of alignment on the y-axis.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "censorize"
msgstr "cenzuri"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Degrade parts of the image in an aesthetically pleasing way, in order to anonymize people/objects or hide body parts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Censorize works in linear RGB color space to apply a physically-accurate gaussian blur and gaussian luminance noise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Aside from anonymization, this module can also be used for a wide range of creative purposes, for example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"- Combine a simple blur with a multiply [blend mode](../masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md) to create a realistic bloom (Orton effect).\n"
"- Combine a simple blur with a subtract blending mode and low opacity to create an [unsharp mask](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unsharp_masking), similar to the [sharpen](./sharpen.md) module but in an RGB scene-referred space.\n"
"- Add noise to create artificial grain.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** The anonymizing methods provided by this module are not forensically safe in order to favor aesthetics. Some forensic techniques may still be able to reconstruct the censorized content based on its structure, especially for simple shapes and text (e.g. license plates, street numbers).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If forensically safe anonymization is required, the only way to achieve this is to paint the surfaces with a solid color.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**The Ansel team does not accept responsibility for poorly anonymized pictures leading to the identification of individuals or personal property.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/diffuse.md
#, fuzzy, no-wrap
#| msgid "workflow overview"
msgid "workflow"
msgstr "superrigardo de laborfluo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You are advised to leave the module's controls at their default values while you [mask](../masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) the areas of the image that you wish to censorize, in order that the details of the image remain visible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input blur radius\n"
": The strength of the first pass of the gaussian blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pixellation radius\n"
": The size of the \"big pixels\" created after the first pass of gaussian blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"output blur radius\n"
": The strength of the second pass of the gaussian blur, applied after the pixellation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"noise level\n"
": The strength (standard deviation) of the luminance gaussian noise applied after the second pass of the gaussian blur. Adding noise can fake details in the blurred regions and make content detection more difficult for artificial intelligence algorithms.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "white balance"
msgstr "blanka ekvilibrio"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Adjust the white balance of the image by altering the temperature and tint, defining a coefficient for each RGB channel, or choosing from list of predefined white balance settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The default settings for this module are derived from the camera white balance stored in the image's Exif data.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "White balance is not intended as a \"creative\" module -- its primary goal is to technically correct the white balance of the image ensuring that neutral colored objects in the scene are rendered with neutral colors in the image. For creative color operations, it is usually better to use other modules such as [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) or [_color balance rgb_](./color-balance-rgb.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** The [_color calibration_](./color-calibration.md) module now provides a more modern and flexible method of controlling white balance. The _color calibration_ module can be enabled by default for new images by selecting \"modern\" in [preferences > processing > auto-apply chromatic adaptation defaults](../../../preferences-settings/processing.md). Some basic settings are still required (and applied automatically) in the _white balance_ module, so that [_demosaic_](./demosaic.md) works correctly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "scene illuminant temp"
msgstr "tempuraturo de scena lumigilo"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This section provides scene-illuminant _temperature_ and _tint_ controls to adjust the white balace of the image. Click on the 'scene illuminant temp' section label to cycle between 3 different [color modes](#colored-sliders) for the temperature/tint sliders.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"temperature\n"
": Set the color temperature in kelvin.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"tint\n"
": Alter the color tint of the image, from magenta (tint < 1) to green (tint > 1).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "white balance presets"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"setting\n"
": Choose from a predetermined list of white balances. The available settings are derived from the presets available in the camera used to take the photograph. The following options are provided in addition to any camera-defined white balance presets.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": - _as shot_ (default): The white balance as reported by the camera\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": - _from image area_: Draw a rectangle over a neutral color in the image to calculate white balance from that area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": - _user modified_: The most recently modified setting. Manual adjustment of temperature, tint or r/g/b channel coefficients will automatically select this option. Choose this setting after selecting any other preset to return parameters to the most recent user-modified state\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ": - _camera reference_: Set the temperature to the camera reference white point, which is assumed to be D65 (or ~6502K). The white balance channel multipliers are calculated such that pure white in the camera colorspace is converted into pure white in sRGB D65 (where pure white means that each color channel has an equal value).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "For convenience the final four modes can also be set by clicking on one of the buttons in the [button bar](#button-bar) above the _setting_ drop-down.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"finetune\n"
": Finetune a camera-specific white balance preset. This is only shown if it is available for the camera in question. The direction of adjustment is dependent on the provided presets. If your camera doesn't have white balance presets available, check [this guide](https://github.com/darktable-org/darktable/wiki/White-balance-presets) to see how you can submit your own.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "channel coefficients"
msgstr "kanalaj koeficientoj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The RGB channel coefficients are automatically calculated from the above parameters and, as such, are hidden by default. You can expand/collapse the channel coefficients section by clicking on either the 'channel coefficients' label or the adjacent triangular button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"red/green/blue\n"
": Set the value of each RGB channel coefficient from 0 to 8\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "additional functionality"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "colored sliders"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default the module's sliders are monochrome. However, two flavors of colored sliders can be enabled in [preferences > darkroom > white balance slider colors](../../../preferences-settings/darkroom.md) or by clicking on the 'scene illuminant temp' section label in the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"no color (default)\n"
": The background of the sliders is not colored.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"illuminant color\n"
": The slider colors represent the color of the light source (the color you are adjusting to in order to achieve neutral white).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"effect emulation\n"
": The slider colors represent the effect the adjustment would have had on the scene. This is how most other raw processors show temperature/tint sliders colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "button bar"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The button bar is simple addition that allows one-click access to the internal white balance settings. You can disable this by editing your `Anselrc` file. Find the line that says\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "plugins/darkroom/temperature/button_bar=TRUE\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "and change `TRUE` to `FALSE`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "usage warning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The only parameters that are used internally by this module's operation are the _rgb channel coefficients_. The _temperature_ and _tint_ sliders are provided as a more user-friendly way to adjust those parameters. The relationship between the channel coefficients and temperature/tint sliders depends on characteristics specific to the camera used to take the photograph. This means that applying white balance settings from an image made with one camera to an image made with another will, in general, not give consistent results.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/white-balance.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "The mathematical relationship between the two sets of values is not straightforward. It is possible to set the channel coefficients such that there is no valid equivalent temperature and tint setting (mainly where very high temperature values are calculated from the sliders). Editing white balance using temperature and tint on an image previously edited using channel coefficients may therefore give odd results, at least where high temperature values are involved.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "hot pixels"
msgstr "varmegaj pikseloj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automatically detect and eliminate hot pixels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Hot pixels are pixels which have failed to record a light level correctly. Detected hot pixels are replaced by an average of their neighbors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"threshold\n"
": How strong a pixel's value needs to deviate from that of its neighbors to be regarded as a hot pixel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"strength\n"
": The blending strength of the hot pixels with their surrounding.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"detect by 3 neighbours\n"
": Extend the detection of hot pixels -- regard a pixel as hot if a minimum of only three (instead of four) neighbor pixels deviate by more than the threshold level.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/hot-pixels.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mark fixed pixels\n"
": Visually mark the corrected pixels on the image and display a count of hot pixels that have been fixed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "graduated density"
msgstr "gradigita denseco"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Simulate a graduated density filter in order to correct exposure and color in a progressive manner.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "A line is shown on screen allowing the position and rotation of the gradient to be modified with the mouse.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "This module is known to provoke banding artifacts under certain conditions. You should consider activating the [_dithering_](./dithering.md) module to alleviate these issues.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"density\n"
": Set the density of the filter (EV). A low value underexposes slightly whereas a high value creates a strong filter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hardness\n"
": The progressiveness of the gradient. A low value creates a smooth transition, whereas a high value makes the transition more abrupt.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"rotation\n"
": The rotation of the filter. Negative values rotate clockwise. The rotation can also be set by dragging the end of the gradient line with the mouse.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": Choose a hue to add a color cast to the gradient.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": The saturation of the color cast to add to the gradient (defaults to a neutral color cast of 0)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "chromatic aberrations"
msgstr "kromataj aberacioj"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Correct chromatic aberrations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "In contrast to the [_raw chromatic aberrations_](./raw-chromatic-aberrations.md) module, this module does not require raw data as input.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To obtain the best result, you are advised to proceed as follows:\n"
"1. Attenuate the chromatic aberrations as much as possible in the [_lens correction_](./lens-correction.md) module using the TCA sliders.\n"
"2. Increase the strength slider in this module to better see its effect.\n"
"3. Increase the radius until the chromatic aberrations disappear. If this is insufficient, try enabling the \"very large chromatic aberrations\" setting.\n"
"4. Choose the guide that gives the best result in term of sharpness and artifacts.\n"
"5. Reduce the strength to avoid washing out the colors too much.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"For more complicated cases you could also try the following:\n"
"- Use several instances with different correction modes -- for example, a first instance in \"brighten only\" mode, and a second in \"darken only\" mode.\n"
"- Use several instances with low strength to correct the chromatic aberrations a little at a time without degrading colors too much.\n"
"- Use the module with parametric or drawn masks.\n"
"- Use RGB red, green and blue blend modes to restrict the effect to a particular channel.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"guide\n"
": The color channel that will be used as a reference for the correction.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"radius\n"
": The radius of the effect. Increase until chromatic aberrations are eliminated. This is the most important slider of the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"strength\n"
": This slider acts as a safeguard and can help to preserve colorful areas that do not suffer from chromatic aberrations. Increase for stronger correction, decrease for stronger preservation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"correction mode\n"
": Allows you to restrict the effect to brighten or darken pixels only. For full control, this can be used in combination with R, G, B blend modes and multiples instances.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"very large chromatic aberrations\n"
": Makes the algorithm iterative to help in reducing very large chromatic aberrations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Yaml Front Matter Hash Value: title
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/negadoctor.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "negadoctor"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/negadoctor.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "Process scanned film negatives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/negadoctor.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can obtain an image of a negative using a film scanner, or by photographing it against a white light (e.g. a light table or computer monitor) or off-camera flash.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/negadoctor.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "preparation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/negadoctor.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the image of the negative was obtained using a digital camera, then in order to obtain accurate colors in the final image, you will need to take the following points into consideration:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/negadoctor.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "- When taking the photograph, adjust the exposure to fully utilise the entire dynamic range of your camera sensor -- i.e. \"expose-to-the-right\", so that the histogram in your camera touches the right hand side without clipping the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/negadoctor.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "- Ensure the white balance is correctly set up to compensate for the light source used to illuminate the negative. You can take a profiling picture of the light source with no film negative in front of it, and then use the \"from image area\" feature in the [_white balance_](./white-balance.md) module to obtain a reference white-balance setting. This reference white balance setting can then be made into a style or simply pasted onto the images taken from your film negatives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/views/darkroom/modules/negadoctor.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "- Apply the standard or enhanced camera matrix in the [_input color profile_](./input-color-profile.md) module.\n"
